Giant telcos Safaricom has partnered with the Kenya Alliance of Resident Associations to beef up security in neighbourhoods, in its efforts to promote sustainable cities and communities.Under the partnership, Safaricom will cooperate with residents associations in laying out and maintaining telecommunication infrastructure for use in deploying technology to enhance security. The telco will also facilitate training on health and environmental awareness.Speaking during the signing of a memorandum of understanding by the two organisations, Safaricom CEO Bob Collymore said the cooperation provides a framework to leverage on technology, to address challenges in the neighbourhoods.&ldquo;Technology offers huge opportunity to enhance the quality of life in neighbourhoods across the country. This partnership opens the door in co-creating solutions that will promote sustainable development in our neighbourhoods. This is in line with our agenda to transform lives of Kenyans,&rdquo; Collymore said. KARA is an umbrella organisation made up of more than 1,000 residents associations from across the country. KARA CEO Henry Ochieng&rsquo; said the partnership with Safaricom is a boost to the organisation&rsquo;s efforts.